
1. ==General Information & Purpose==

- **Product Name:** Smart Lighting Ecosystem (SLE)
- **Status:** In Development
- **Version:** 2.1
- **Target Release Date:** Q2 2026
- **Product Manager:** Nazar Lebedenko
- **Executive Summary:** An automated, edge-based lighting system that regulates indoor color temperature based on real-time environmental Lux and solar position. It solves the problem of circadian disruption caused by artificial bright light exposure in the evenings.

2. ==Goals & Success Metrics==

- **Project Goal:** Create a high-fidelity, documented IoT project for personal use and online distribution. Use AI chat-bot assistance to maximize speed of development and testing.  
- **User Problem:** Artificial indoor lighting suppresses melatonin production in the evening, leading to suboptimal sleep quality.
- **Key Success Metrics (KPIs):
	- **Connectivity Uptime:** 100% local execution regardless of Internet availability.
	- **Latency:** <200ms from sensor Lux change to bulb state change.
	- **User Outcome:** Measured improvement in subjective sleep quality via journaling or using smartwatch measurements.
	- **Battery Health Monitoring:** System must maintain >95% uptime for the Tuya sensor; trigger a "Low Battery" alert in the dashboard when the CR2032 cell reaches <15%.

3. ==Target Audience & Personas==

- **Key Persona:** Health-conscious users.
- **Use Cases/Scenarios:** 
	- **Sunset Transition:** As the sun sets in Ottawa, the system automatically shifts bulbs to (<2000K) deem and warm light to signal the body to rest.
	- **Cloudy Day Override:** If external light drops significantly, or light sensor gets blocked or runs out of battery the system uses calculated sun position to adjust.
	- **Sunrise Transition:** As the sun rises the system automatically shifts bulbs from the evening deem and warm light to a high-intensity, cool white spectrum (5000K+). This transition suppresses melatonin and triggers the body's natural cortisol awakening response to increase morning alertness.

